                 = \n| area_total_km2                  = 8.47\n| area_land_km2                   = <!--See table @ Template:Infobox Settlement for details on automatic unit conversion-->\n| area_water_km2                  = \n| area_total_sq_mi                = \n| area_land_sq_mi                 = \n| area_water_sq_mi                = \n| area_water_percent              = \n| area_urban_km2                  = \n| area_urban_sq_mi                = \n| area_metro_km2                  = \n| area_metro_sq_mi                = \n| area_blank1_title               = \n| area_blank1_km2                 = \n| area_blank1_sq_mi               = <!-- Population   ----------------------->\n| population_as_of                = 2016\n| population_footnotes            = \n| population_note                 = \n| population_total                = 9,001\n| population_density_km2          = 626.8\n| population_density_sq_mi        = \n| population_metro                = \n| population_density_metro_km2    = \n| population_density_metro_sq_mi  = \n| population_urban                = \n| population_density_urban_km2    = \n| population_density_urban_sq_mi  = \n| population_blank1_title         = \n| population_blank1               = \n| population_density_blank1_km2   = \n| population_density_blank1_sq_mi = <!-- General information  --------------->\n| timezone                        = [[Mountain Time Zone|MST]]<ref name=\"mstdst\">Naniamo Daily News. [https://archive.is/20130118160335/http://www2.canada.com/nanaimodailynews/news/story.html?id=1a68652d-40fb-4926-afa1-cd696e1da3c7 Not everyone's a big fan of annual daylight time switch]. 2012-11-03. Retrieved 2012-11-03.</ref>\n| utc_offset                      = \u221207:00\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|49|05|24|N|116|30|36|W|region:CA-BC|display=inline,title}}|\n| elevation_footnotes             = <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n| elevation_m                     = 597\n| elevation_ft                    = <!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->\n| postal_code_type                = Postal code span\n| postal_code                     = V0B\n| area_code                       = [[Area code 250|250]] / [[Area code 778|778]] / [[Area code 236|236]]\n| blank_name                      = [[List of British Columbia provincial highways|Highways]]\n| blank_info                      = {{jct|state=BC|Hwy|3}} <br> {{jct|state=BC|Hwy|3A}} <br> {{jct|state=BC|Hwy|21}}\n| blank1_name                     = Waterways\n| blank1_info                     = [[Kootenay River]]\n| website                         = [http://www.creston.ca/ Official website]\n| footnotes                       = \n}}\n <!--Infobox ends-->\n[[File:Welcome sign.JPG|thumb|Creston's welcome sign]]\n'''Creston''' is a town of 9,001 people in the [[Kootenays|Kootenay]] region of southeastern [[British Columbia]], Canada.  The town is located approximately {{convert|10|km|abbr=on|sigfig=1}} north of the border crossing into the United States It is about a one-hour drive southwest from [[Cranbrook, British Columbia|Cranbrook]] along the [[Crowsnest Highway]]. Due to its proximity to the U.S. border, many businesses in the town accept American currency. Similarly, [[Porthill, Idaho|Porthill]], the nearby US border town, accepts Canadian currency and sells gasoline in litres.\n\nCreston is the eastern terminus of the [[British Columbia Highway 3|Salmo-Creston highway]] constructed in the 1920s as a shortcut to avoid the long route north to [[Nelson, British Columbia|Nelson]] and crossing [[Kootenay Lake]] on the [[Kootenay Lake Ferry]] between [[Balfour, British Columbia|Balfour]] and [[Kootenay Bay]]. The Salmo-Creston highway, which is part of the Crowsnest Highway, connected with earlier highways eastward of Creston.\n\nCreston is one of the few towns in British Columbia that does not observe [[daylight saving time]].<ref name=\"mstdst\"/>\n\n==Economy==\nThe Creston Valley's economy is largely resource-based with [[agriculture]] and [[forestry]]. Many are employed in the service sector, and [[tourism]] is increasingly prominent, while government services and education<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www12.statcan.ca/english/census06/data/profiles/community/Details/Page_Custom.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=5903004&Geo2=PR&Code2=59&Data=Count&SearchText=creston&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=59&B1=Custom |title=Statistics Canada |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160109163849/http://www12.statcan.ca/english/census06/data/profiles/community/Details/Page_Custom.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=5903004&Geo2=PR&Code2=59&Data=Count&SearchText=creston&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=59&B1=Custom |archivedate=2016-01-09 }}</ref> comprise a large portion of the labour force. Since 1959, [[Kokanee beer]] has been [[brewing|brewed]] in Creston at the [[Columbia Brewery]].<ref>[http://www.columbiabrewery.ca/node/3 \"History\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131013053209/http://www.columbiabrewery.ca/node/3 |date=2013-10-13 }} Columbia Brewery. Retrieved 2013-11-17.</ref>  The town is also home to two [[grain elevator]]s. Many apple, and cherry orchards grow in [[Erickson, British Columbia|Erickson]], an unincorporated area outside of Creston, and the valley is also an important dairy centre. The Creston Area produces the largest cherries{{clarify|date=November 2012}} grown in the northern hemisphere and exports them globally.  A primary market is Europe while Asia is second. A number of growers sell the same product they export to Europe at their road side markets.  The Skimmerhorn Winery<ref>[http://www.skimmerhorn.ca skimmerhorn.ca]</ref> is now producing award-winning wines, and the valley includes other growers cultivating vines.  Creston is home to [[CIDO-FM]], a volunteer-run, locally based, [[community radio]] station, which broadcasts in town, and in the Creston Valley at 97.7 FM.\n\n==Demographics==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Canada 2016 Census!! Population !! % of total population\n|-\n| rowspan=\"12\" | [[Visible minority]] group<br /><small>Source:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/nhs-enm/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=5933042&Data=Count&SearchText=Creston&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&A1=All&B1=All&Custom=&TABID=1Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=5915025&Geo2=PR&Code2=59&Data=Count&SearchText=Creston&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=Visible%20minority&Custom= |title=Community Profiles from the 2011 Census, Statistics Canada \u2013 Census Subdivision |publisher=2.statcan.gc.ca |date=6 December 2010 |accessdate=13 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140410173607/http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/nhs-enm/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=5933042&Data=Count&SearchText=Creston&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&A1=All&B1=All&Custom=&TABID=1Lang%3DE&Geo1=CSD&Code1=5915025&Geo2=PR&Code2=59&Data=Count&SearchText=Creston&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=Visible%20minority&Custom= |archivedate=10 April 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref></small>\n| [[Chinese Canadian|Chinese]] || 10 || {{Percentage | 10 | 5105 | 1}}\n|-\n| [[South Asian Canadian|South Asian]] || 15 || {{Percentage | 15 | 5105 | 1}}\n|-\n| [[Black Canadians|Black]] || 0 || {{Percentage | 0 | 5105 | 1}}\n|-\n| [[Filipino Canadian|Filipino]] || 35 || {{Percentage | 35 | 5105 | 1}}\n|-\n| [[Latin American Canadian|Latin American]] || 0 || {{Percentage | 0 | 5105 | 1}}\n|-\n| [[Arab Canadians|Arab]] || 0 || {{Percentage | 0 | 5105 | 1}}\n|-\n| [[Southeast Asia]]n || 20 || {{Percentage | 20 | 5105 | 1}}\n|-\n| [[Western Asia|West Asian]] || 0 || {{Percentage | 0 | 5105 | 1}}\n|-\n| [[Korean Canadian|Korean]] || 0 || {{Percentage | 0 | 5105 | 1}}\n|-\n| [[Japanese Canadians|Japanese]] || 0 || {{Percentage | 0 | 5105 | 1}}\n|-\n| Other visible minority || 0 || {{Percentage | 0 | 5105 | 1}}\n|-\n| [[Multiracial|Mixed]] visible minority || 0 || {{Percentage | 0 | 5105 | 1}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | Total visible minority population|| 90 || {{Percentage | 90 | 5105 | 1}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[Aboriginal peoples in Canada|Aboriginal]] group<br /><small>Source:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/nhs-enm/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=5933042&Data=Count&SearchText=Creston&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&A1=All&B1=All&Custom=&TABID=1Lang=E&Geo=CSD&Code=59&Table=1&Data=Count&Sex=1&Age=1&StartRec=26&Sort=2&Display=Page&CSDFilter=5000 |title=Aboriginal Peoples \u2013 Data table |publisher=2.statcan.ca |date=6 October 2010 |accessdate=13 April 2013}}</ref></small> || [[First Nations]] || 135 || {{Percentage | 135 | 5100 | 1}}\n|-\n| [[M\u00e9tis people (Canada)|M\u00e9tis]] || 155 || {{Percentage | 155 | 5100 | 1}}\n|-\n| [[Inuit]] || 10 || {{Percentage | 10 | 5100 | 1}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | Total Aboriginal population || 310 || {{Percentage | 310 | 5100 | 1}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[European Canadian]] || 4,705 || {{Percentage | 4705 | 5100 | 1}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | ''Total population'' || ''5,105'' || ''100%''\n|}\n\n==Climate==\nCreston's climate is often modified by air masses of the [[Pacific Ocean]] origin, especially in winter. Daily maximum temperatures are usually above freezing even in January except when air masses of [[Arctic]] origin move over the area. The worst cold outbreaks may send temperatures below {{Convert|-30|C}} on rare occasions. Spring comes early by Canadian standards; trees usually start to leaf out before the end of April. A clear summer day is likely to have a daily maximum near or above {{Convert|25|C}}; the record maximum is {{Convert|39.4|C|0}}. The first fall frost usually holds off until October where air drainage is good.\n\nThe mean annual [[precipitation]] is {{Convert|662.4|mm|abbr=on|2}} in mid-town, but the area has a rather steep precipitation gradient which is reflected in regional ecosystems.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Creston, 1981\u20132010 normals, extremes 1912\u2013present\n|metric f